---
import Base from '../../../layouts/Base.astro';

const photos = Array.from({ length: 14 }, (_, i) => `tabor2022-${String(i + 1).padStart(2, '0')}.jpg`);
---

<Base title="Diaspora School Camp 2022" lang="en" description="Report on the 2022 Diaspora School Camp in Vancouver.">
  <div class="container container--narrow prose">
    <h1 class="page-title">Diaspora School Camp 2022</h1>

    <p>
      After the successful camp three years earlier, the Szent László Hungarian
      School organized this year's camp with the goal of reviving the Hungarian
      community after the pandemic, and with it the desire to learn the Hungarian
      language and culture. We also wanted to give the children attending our
      school — and Hungarian-speaking children of Hungarian descent living in the
      surrounding area — an opportunity to deepen their Hungarian, and to get to
      know Hungary's history, geography, cultural treasures, and traditions. The
      camp was a day camp this year rather than residential, running from 9 a.m.
      to 5 p.m. The Our Lady of Hungary parish, which provides our classrooms
      during the school year, hosted the camp as well, so we could use the stage
      and the main hall, while sports sessions were held in the park and
      playground a five-minute walk from the school. During the organizing, a
      grandmother wrote to enrol her grandchildren, who were visiting from
      Montreal. It turned out her daughter had studied at the Szent László School
      before moving to Montreal, where she is an active member and teacher of the
      Hungarian school there. In the end, she took on teaching one of the groups.
      A fantastic example that — although we live 3,700 km apart — we support each
      other when needed.
    </p>
    <p>
      The camp was wonderfully balanced, and our time together passed in great
      spirits. The camp's theme — the folk tale — proved to be a splendid choice:
      every age group loves listening to them, and they speak to everyone in some
      way. Everyone loves to tell stories and daydream, as we experienced once
      again. Based on the feedback, the children thoroughly enjoyed the week. We
      started with 25 children, but in one family the two older kids told so many
      stories at home that the youngest joined mid-week. When the camp ended, one
      parent wrote that her little boy woke up on Saturday morning saying: let's
      go to Hungarian camp — but this time not for five days, that's too short;
      make it eight. We could not have received greater praise!
    </p>
    <p>
      The campers' language skills ranged from basic Hungarian-as-a-foreign-language
      to near-perfect. We deepened the children's Hungarian partly through constant
      Hungarian speech and partly through the daily sessions — for that week, the
      camp functioned as a little Hungarian island.
    </p>
    <p>
      The days were organized around five different themes, each also touching on
      Hungarian grammar, literature, history, and geography. Teaching was playful,
      using the tools of experiential pedagogy. Every child received a folder to
      collect the week's material in, and on Friday every age group proudly showed
      theirs to their parents. This year's novelty was the camp T-shirt, which the
      children wore with great joy. Dance instruction ran in two groups: the little
      ones were just getting to know the basics, while the older ones already
      managed more serious steps. The week's closing event was Friday's puppet
      show. In the morning the children picked their favourites from the school's
      puppets, then together we wrote a tale, which we performed on stage. It was
      wonderful to see how creatively they crafted the camp's tale from folk-tale
      elements after a week of active story listening and reading. The planned
      program was realized to the fullest. We closed a rich, lively, good-spirited
      camp — one we would love to continue in the years to come.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="container">
    <div class="gallery">
      {photos.map((img, i) => (
        <a href={`/images/${img}`} target="_blank">
          <img src={`/images/${img}`} alt={`Diaspora School Camp 2022 – photo ${i + 1}`} loading="lazy" />
        </a>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>
</Base>
